\fs32 Parallel Pipelining\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f3 \cf2 Powershell 7 introduced the new parallel parameter for the ForEach-Object cmdlet, which allows you to run a script block in parallel for each element in a collection.\'a0
\f0 \

\f3 In prior versions of Powershell, if you pass an array of 10 objects such as event logs, it would run the code for eac hobject in sequential series. If we sent an array with numbers 1-10 and put the program to sleep for 1second each, it would be approximately 10 seconds.\'a0
\f0 \

\f3 But with PS7 we can run this in parallel even though it is an array. We can also set a throttle limit to make sure that the processes don't overstep their capabilities. So here, if we set the throttle limit to 10, then each member of the array will run in parallel and the entire process, even though each array member is still sleeping for 1second, it will fully complete in about 1 second as all 10 array members go in parallel.\'a0\'a0
\f0 \

\f3 If done correctly and accounting for a systems resources, this can greatly speed up a process especially when doing something like searching through different event logs.\'a0\'a0
